event_info: {"user_text":"A fun light read! It’s an excellent look into the real lifestyle of a fed-up fitness blogger, confirming what so many people already half-know: fitness isn’t the key to happiness and it’s nowhere near as easy as Instagram makes it look. Packed with a great cast of characters, comic mishaps and a teenage character who is easier to empathise with than her mother, this book is great for kicking back and relaxing, and reminding yourself that happiness isn’t a goal but an emotion."}

event_info:
{"highlighted_text":"quietened to a few mere shuffles and gasps. Even those subsided within seconds, like coughs at a recital. The chatter of a hundred mouths stopped, as if they had been gagged.

 

Beyond her - beyond the scene and heedless of the shocked pause it demanded of the onlookers - the world continued. Raindrops broke on the windows; a bird sang in imitation of a mobile phone. In the distance, a door slammed somewhere - the wind must have closed it, because all human activity was, for now, on hiatus for this frozen moment. For her"}

event_info:
{"highlighted_text":"It looked like she had fallen from the sky.

 

She was lying on the floor in front of them all, a small puddle of black ink blooming next to her head.

 

The drum and thud of footfalls died as shoes slowed and stopped, then began to arrange themselves around her.. The busy swish of people passing quietened to a few mere shuffles and gasps. Even those subsided within seconds, like coughs at a recital. The chatter of a hundred mouths stopped, as if they had been gagged.

 

Beyond her - beyond the scene and heedless of the shocked pause it demanded of the onlookers - the world continued. Raindrops broke on the windows; a bird sang in imitation of a mobile phone. In the distance, a door slammed somewhere - the wind must have closed it, because all human activity was, for now, on hiatus for this frozen moment. For her"}

event_info:
{"highlight_id":293592,"highlighted_text":"It looked like she had fallen from the sky.

 

She was lying on the floor in front of them all, a small puddle of black ink blooming next to her head.

 

The drum and thud of footfalls died as shoes slowed and stopped, then began to arrange themselves around her.. The busy swish of people passing quietened to a few mere shuffles and gasps. Even those subsided within seconds, like coughs at a recital. The chatter of a hundred mouths stopped, as if they had been gagged.

 

Beyond her - beyond the scene and heedless of the shocked pause it demanded of the onlookers - the world continued. Raindrops broke on the windows; a bird sang in imitation of a mobile phone. In the distance, a door slammed somewhere - the wind must have closed it, because all human activity was, for now, on hiatus for this frozen moment. For her","user_text":"How do I delete a highlight? event_info: {"highlighted_text":"It was then that something odd happened to Margot. One minute, she’d been checking her phone - that quick email refresh and catch-up that has become acceptable even when someone is talking to you. The next, she was pale and trembling, her lips white against grey, clammy skin in which her eyes stood out, urgent and piercing. Staring at Maggie but also through her, the sinews in her neck taut"}

{"highlighted_text":"When morning finally came, bringing with it a weekend of grey skies and parent-to-be chores, Nick woke to find my side of the bed empty. I had cleaned the house from top to bottom, gone for a walk, bought breakfast things and read the paper on the iPad. He congratulated me on a day well spent. No need for him to know that, in those dark hours, I had also given up hope that my own child would survive birth or, in the unlikely event that it did, live much beyond the age of five."}
{"highlighted_text":"I’m Margot Jones, I’m nearly eighteen weeks pregnant, and I’m the fashion editor at Lucky magazine.”"}

{"highlighted_text":"You were so enthusiastic, so excitable,” the smooth voice continued in her ear. “So many people in this job are so jaded. It was enlivening to speak to someone who clearly wasn’t worried about being cool.”"}

event_info: {"highlighted_text":"Do you think our grannies pored over sepia photographs of their neighbours and felt like shit? Maggie didn’t either.\n\n "}

{"highlighted_text":"Fashion wasn’t at all about clothes, it was about the person wearing them and whether they’re found worthy of admiration. And that’s when she had an idea that she knew Emily Moffatt would love."}
{"highlighted_text":"On the counter, her phone buzzed with a message: “We’ll make you fabulous,” it said, “plenty of Photoshop"}
{"highlighted_text":"Not a woman to spare anybody’s feelings, Emily Moffatt.\n\n "}

{"highlighted_text":"Maggie had always wanted to wear clothes like that, but she’d look like she was on her way to a nostalgia event. She made a hasty note in her pad for the piece about how the line between style and costume is blurred for fashion editors."}

{"highlighted_text":"Can’t wait to see you in the office when you start,” Holly said, as her assistants packed away the clothes and Maggie peeled off a set of false eyelashes in front of the bulb-framed vanity mirror"}

{"highlighted_text":"She and the rest of the crew had joked that the new girl was a natural.

 

“Margot will have to watch out!” Holly called, smiling, as Maggie climbed into her second taxi of the day"}

event_info: {"highlighted_text":"Maggie,” Moff said at conversational volume, barely audible over the chairs scraping and chit-chat, “can you stay please?”"}
{"highlighted_text":"I’m aware that out there” - Moff gestured to the office beyond her frosted windows - “the girls call me Moff.” She pursed her lips. “But "}
{"highlighted_text":" you really think they called me it to my face?”"}

{"highlighted_text":"She wasn’t worried about me messing up, Maggie realised suddenly. She was annoyed to hear that I hadn’t. It had only been a matter of seconds before Margot had laughed along with her, but it was just enough time to let slip that she "}

{"highlighted_text":"Winnie knows exactly which buttons to press.

 

The thought bounced into my head before I could stop it, but it sounded ludicrous even to me.

 

Helen knows.

 

But that was impossible."}
{"highlighted_text":"Somewhere near its centre, a blonde woman was flapping her hands to hush and divert attention back to the toast, but it was too late."}

{"highlighted_text":"They had all been at the bottom of the box Winnie had returned, a scene of rage daubed in serums and lotions, the jars with their lids twisted off, tubes squeezed out, so that they had coated the other items in the box in a gloopy layer"}
{"highlighted_text":"My heart broke again and with it, my waters."}

{"highlighted_text":" soon as she realised that, Maggie began introducing herself to people. And as soon as she did that, they went from frosty hauteur to smiles, wisecracks and “hi Maggie!” from across the room, waving and pointing out her seat next to them. She didn’t know whether it was shyness"}

{"highlighted_text":"In Paris now she finally voiced what she could no longer ignore, breathing it into life over the most stylish city in the world:

 

“I don’t ever want to give this job back."}

{"highlighted_text":"Very common in new mothers,” the doctor said, when I explained my fears on Nick’s gentle suggestion. “What you’re actually seeing are the dangers, Margot. It’s just your mind warning you. It’s normal"}

event_info: {"user_text":"What an introduction to Secret Readers! I was mesmerised by this book. It was refreshingly different and I became completely involved with the main characters within the first few pages.  It became difficult to continue once I knew what the final outcome would be but I simply had to continue to the end, despite using tissues galore! A fantastic book which will remain with me always. I will be recommending it wholeheartedly to all my friends and family and have already earmarked it to give to my granddaughter as soon as it’s published."}

event_info: {"user_text":"I wouldn't normally read a romance book but it looked the least chicklit out of the four to choose from. I'm glad I did, it was a great read. the main man was adorably real, and the way you get to find out how the first time they met unfolds throughout the book is cleverly done. you want to know what happens next, all the way through the book. it's not like any 'romance' tripe I avoid like the plague. I would not have bought this in a million years, but really glad I read it. "}

event_info: {"highlighted_text":"I wasn’t surprised when, just before sunrise one morning, I saw Winnie had un-friended me on Facebook. Wasn’t surprised, though it came as yet another jolt to a body that was still raw with new motherhood"}

{"highlighted_text":"She’s treating me like I wronged her. All I did was have a baby.

 

But I knew that was not exactly true.

 

**

 

It was a Tuesday when I first saw Winnie in my neighbourhood."}

{"highlighted_text":"Winnie knelt in front of one of the stones, her ginger hair, the same colour as the turning leaves along the path, clearly visible above it. I didn’t need to see my friend’s face to know it was her. I felt her proximity like an electric current. Without thinking, I quickened my pace until I reached the next copse of mis-shapen tombs, took the nearest exit and went straight home"}

event_info: {"highlighted_text":"Margot probably didn’t even notice these small acts of spite because she was operating on a higher level these days. The realisation had not made Maggie feel good."}

{"highlighted_text":"So you’re Nick’s brother, is that right?” she asked him, reasoning dejectedly that family was probably off-limits to someone currently moonlighting as Margot in her second most important relationship"}
{"highlighted_text":"His best friend.” Margot looked up at Tim affectionately, made a top-up gesture towards somebody behind her and disappeared back into the throng"}

{"highlighted_text":"Charles jumped slightly when I opened the door, as if he was as startled as I was at the fact of him being there on our front step. My first thought: I wondered if Winnie knew her husband had come here, whether she had sent him. Or had he come without telling her?"}

{"highlighted_text":"Nevertheless, I was glad of my quick reaction. I was happy to see Charles, grateful for the empathy he had offered. But I didn’t want him near Lila. I still felt too sick about Winnie."}

{"highlighted_text":"When she asked if there were any questions, Maggie had a sudden revelation. This was just like the few days they’d shared in the office before the handover. Margot had been in a position of if not exactly power over her replacement, but of advanced expertise. And now—like then—she positively glowed with it."}

{"highlighted_text":"By contrast, the carefully compartmentalised bag that hung from Lila’s pram and contained the baby’s nappies and wipes, milk, a change of clothes, sunhat and bottle of Calpol spoke of a serene and settled mind. Or of a psychopath, Maggie supposed, repressing a smile."}

{"highlighted_text":"The server dithered, having confused her herbal tea with another customer’s. It only took a minute or so, but suddenly she felt nervous. She shouldn’t have turned her back on Lila for more than a few seconds"}
{"highlighted_text":"But it was the other woman’s face, as it turned to look up at her on the stairs, that sent a chill through Maggie"}
{"highlighted_text":"sending me a picture of herself with Lila gurgling next to her, "}

{"highlighted_text":"\n“I’m fine, Maggie, thank you,” I lied, affecting bashfulness. “I guess I just haven’t left Lila for that long before and I got a bit anxious, that’s all. Quite highly strung at the best of times"}

{"highlighted_text":"I had to stay sharp for this, which meant Nick couldn’t know. For now.

 

Clever Winnie to make it all look so ordinary. You’d have to know everything to understand the threat she was sending"}

event_info: {"highlighted_text":"Just as there was no punctuation in Winnie’s message, so there was no overt animosity. Her first move was a blank, an empty version of how we both felt, a step taken in the dark without knowing whether there was firm ground to land on"}

event_info: {"user_text":"Everything is Fine – Gillian Harvey\r\rThe story is of Jessica’s life her PR business her family and her relationships.  It is hilarious and heart-warming, a roller coaster of emotions I was laughing one minute and feeling very sad the next.\rI loved Jessica her family and friends apart from Dave bless him. They weren’t perfect but they all had this wonderful relationship with lots of banter.\rI was disappointed that there wasn’t a definitive ending I wasn’t sure if she would fall in love with the guy, I wanted her to, but fingers crossed!\rIt is the type of book you can enjoy snuggled in a chair, on holiday on a bus or train.\rBut I really enjoyed the story 5 stars."}

event_info: {"highlighted_text":"I let Margot understand that, if she ever left me, I could ruin her life at a stroke: all I needed to do was change my statement with the police: “You were taunting her. I know what you did.” I’d always been the one in charge of our friendship, the one who decided where we went on a Saturday and what we bought, what music we liked, how we cut our hair or what colour we painted our nails. Now I was in charge of her future, too"}

event_info: {"highlighted_text":"I still couldn’t bring myself to hate Maggie outright: there was too much of myself in the woman currently occupying my desk - the same humour, the shared tastes, so similar a personality type it was as though we’d known each other for years. At first, I had thought of my replacement as a reflection in a fairground mirror, myself in antithesis: short where I was tall, dark where I was fair, pretty where I was severe, and outgoing where I was painfully shy. More recently though, I had felt in Maggie’s company a rippling sensation, a stirring of memories and of familiarity surfacing as if from somewhere dark within me"}

{"highlighted_text":"“My baby…”

 

“No, Margot,” Winnie said, in a low voice, with a finality that turned the blood in my veins to solid ice.

 

“She isn’t yours,” Winnie said. Her gaze flitted about, unable to focus on me. The wildness in her eyes, the twitching of her head: Winnie seemed to vibrate with nervous energy. With rage.

 "}

{"highlighted_text":"“It isn’t me you need to be afraid of,” Winnie said, carefully.

 

I saw that she was frightened, too.

 

A movement then, and I made out another shape up there in the shadows behind her.

 

“Let me help you, Win,” a voice said in the dark. “You don’t need to hurt anymore.”"}

event_info: {"highlighted_text":"Charles’s head snapped up at the male voice, and the despair on his features rearranged itself to anger. All the hatred, the resentment and the envy I had imagined coming off Winnie in waves towards me throughout my maternity leave I saw broadcast in her husband’s face, and I knew once and for all who had sent me all those messages, who had left the mixtape for me to find.\n\n "}

event_info:
{"user_text":"This great book isn’t out yet, but you need to preorder this for sure.

This isn’t a soppy romance or full of sex and lust, it’s a purely remarkable sad but uplifting tale in the entire meaning of love. Self sacrificing love at its upmost. And yes, it will most probably make you cry big tears yet also with a contented smile on your face.

This was so well written, I sure had a job to put this down at times so I could get on with other things that needed my attention, yet, I couldn’t wait to get back to my book.

That’s a good sign for me.

The start of the book the chapters seem long but they get shorter as you go and this picks up pace as it’s viewpoints and feelings from both main characters, I was turning the pages so fast.

I really recommend this one. I’m not a lover of “romance” this is in a different league.

Adored it"}

event_info:
{"user_text":"I was given access to this via Secret Readers...and I’m so pleased I chose this title. I’m pretty sure that upon its release (scheduled for June 2020) this will become a much talked-about read, and I’m pretty convinced it will be turned into a film before long.
The Sight of You is a romance of epic proportions, but not quite in the way you might expect.
Joel has always had startlingly accurate dreams about people he loves. As a result he has vowed never to fall in love, because the pressure of seeing something you cannot change is too much. Yet when he meets Callie, it seems inevitable they’ll end up together.
The initial stages of the book had me entranced, but in a mildly curious way as I wondered just where this would go. Their fledgling relationship is cute, and having both perspectives definitely took this out of the standard romance vein I was expecting.
However, once we see how things pan out and see the depth of Joel’s love for Callie I am not afraid to admit to being totally emotionally overcome by this. Much as it didn’t follow the path you might have thought you wanted it to, it ended on such a positively life-affirming tone. 
A testimony to love, in its truest form."}

event_info: {"user_text":"I quite liked reading this, easy to read chick lit type book. I would have given it four stars, and actually did initially, but after having thought about it for a few days I'm now giving it three. I found Dave a confusing, unconvincing character. Dumps her via post it, but allows her to pretend they're together, then proposes, while constantly body shaming her. And the body shaming is why I'm also giving it three stars. It was just too much, as was the repeated suggestion that her husband would actually leave her for someone with bigger boobs, because that's a reason for leaving a marriage. A shame, because I did enjoy the social media side of it."}

event_info: {"user_text":"I enjoyed this book, it was an easy read. It was fun but also had an important message about social media and image! You shouldn't let it take over your life and ruin your relationships. It also showed a toxic relationship and how that can also affect your life, nobody who claims to love you should only want you when you are skinny and picture perfect. There was a lot of overly cringy moments that I wasn't to sure of, there didn't need to be so much going wrong! I could kind of relate to the main character but I didn't really like her at times! Overall a fun easy read with some real world issues. "}
